WHAT THE ORGANISATION DOES:
Break supports children, young people and families in four key areas - young people in care and moving on, children and young people with disabilities, families in need of support and children at risk.

ORGANISATION CONTEXT:
Norwich, Norfolk, Norfolk. ~350 staff; income on record £12,000,000.

RECOMMENDED VAxAI ENTRY: Training + workflow review

WHY ADMIN / AI PRESSURE IS HIGH:
Children''s homes, leaving-care, mental health and community services span regulated placements, rotas, HR and funder evidence.

CHARITY / SECTOR AI CONTEXT (use in conversation):
Care charities face high data sensitivity. AI adoption is cautious; practical wins are usually in rota coordination, care note drafting support, and training rather than automated decision-making.

WHERE VA ALONE IS NOT THE RIGHT LEAD:
Avoid leading with VA for regulated care documentation — start with policy, training, and workflow review with safeguarding oversight.

STRONGEST REASON TO CONTACT:
Break shows care & supported living delivery with material admin load — VAT-informed review of where AI can assist without touching safeguarding decisions

HOW TO PRESENT VAxAI:
Position VAxAI as wraparound support: review existing systems, train staff on practical AI, and offer flexible virtual assistance for follow-through — not a CRM or case-system replacement.

SUGGESTED CALL HOOKS / DISCOVERY QUESTIONS:
• VAT-informed review of where AI can assist without touching safeguarding decisions
• Workflow review across rotas, care plans, and funder evidence
• Upskill team leads on practical AI drafting with audit trails

DISCOVERY PROMPTS FOR THIS CALL:
• Which reporting, referral, or volunteer workflows consume the most coordinator time?
• What systems are in use today — and where do spreadsheets or email still carry the load?
